{"paperId": "bd8ab487b7a33a9b37b04b4a184b963744394320", "title": "DEERE: Document-Level Event Extraction as Relation Extraction", "abstract": "The descriptions of complex events usually span sentences, so we need to extract complete event information from the whole document. To address the challenges of document-level event extraction, we propose a novel framework named Document-level Event Extraction as Relation Extraction (DEERE), which is suitable for document-level event extraction tasks without trigger-word labelling. By well-designed task transformation, DEERE remodels event extraction as single-stage relation extraction, which can mitigate error propagation. A long text supported encoder is adopted in the relation extraction model to aware the global context effectively. A fault-tolerant event integration algorithm is designed to improve the prediction accuracy. Experimental results show that our approach advances the SOTA for the ChFinAnn dataset by an average F1-score of 3.7. The code and data are available at https://github.com/maomaotfntfn/DEERE.", "venue": "Mobile Information Systems", "year": 2022, "citationCount": 0, "influentialCitationCount": 0, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://downloads.hindawi.com/journals/misy/2022/2742796.pdf", "status": "GOLD"}, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "This work proposes a novel framework named Document-level Event Extraction as Relation Extraction (DEERE), which is suitable for document-level event extraction tasks without trigger-word labelling, and remodels event extraction as single-stage relation extraction, which can mitigate error propagation."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [-0.07364070415496826, 0.6543391942977905, -0.4706387221813202, -0.21504169702529907, -4.037197413708782e-06, -0.2823622524738312, 0.9578114748001099, 0.16178032755851746, -0.37075719237327576, -0.03872525319457054, 0.7832188606262207, 0.5072329044342041, 0.21502867341041565, -0.02693110518157482, 0.301256597042083